---

## Abstract

Emotional wellbeing and personalized support represent fundamental challenges across diverse human-centered applications, from mental health assistance and educational guidance to customer service and workplace coaching. While conversational AI offers scalable solutions for emotional support and personalized interaction, many existing digital assistants remain generic and fail to adapt to users' individual personality differences, limiting their effectiveness in providing contextually appropriate assistance. This master's thesis specifies a modular, workflow-orchestrated architecture for personality-aware dialogue that integrates Big Five (OCEAN) personality detection with Zurich Model-aligned behavior regulation to create a reusable research infrastructure supporting domain-specific applications.

Building on Devdas (2025), who demonstrated substantial performance gains using a detection→regulation→generation pipeline, this work extends that foundation by developing a production-ready, reusable system architecture optimized for temporal stability, reproducibility, and cross-domain deployment. The system integrates a workflow orchestration backend with a RESTful frontend API, enabling clean separation between conversation logic and user interface delivery. Five architectural enhancements collectively advance the approach: (1) temporal smoothing with exponential moving average (EMA) stabilizes personality assessment across conversation turns, reducing response variability; (2) confidence-aware filtering ensures the system acts only on reliable trait readings; (3) configurable, extensible workflow design enables domain adaptation through policy-pack reconfiguration rather than code modification; (4) comprehensive logging with audit trails supports rigorous analysis and reproducibility; and (5) domain-specific policy packs encapsulate coaching modes, regulation rules, and behavioral directives, allowing rapid transfer across application contexts such as stress coaching, customer service, or education. The system adapts conversational tone, pacing, warmth, and novelty proportionally to detected trait profiles, with all responses grounded in the user's actual statements to prevent fabricated information.

The architecture is demonstrated through a **Workplace Adaptive Resilience Coach** addressing workplace stress in contemporary organizations. The system offers three personality-tailored coaching modes: Vent & Validate provides empathetic listening for emotionally sensitive users (high neuroticism), addressing their need for validation and emotional processing; Plan & Structure offers goal-oriented guidance for organized, disciplined users (high conscientiousness), supporting structured problem-solving; and Cope & Rehearse equips users with practical stress management strategies adaptable across personality profiles. Evaluation employs structured rubrics assessing detection accuracy (correct Big Five trait identification via sentiment, word choice, and syntactic patterns), tone appropriateness (response alignment with personality-specific needs), trait detection stability (consistent assessments across conversation turns, ensuring reliable personalization and building user trust), and user satisfaction (measured through 5-point Likert-scale post-interaction surveys). The framework supports future applications in mental health and educational contexts beyond the current thesis scope. The outcome is a reproducible, research-grade infrastructure bridging personality psychology theory with operational AI systems. The thesis phase includes A/B comparison studies to optimize personalization strategies and human validation studies to confirm response effectiveness and user engagement.

**Keywords:** personality-aware chatbot; OCEAN personality detection; Zurich Model; conversational AI; behavior regulation; workflow orchestration; personality adaptation; dialog grounding; human-centered AI; emotional support systems

